external_knowledge:
- 'Above-average overall performance' implies OPR greater than 20;
- 'Rounds that aren't too far into the competition' refers to rounds numbered between 1 and 5;
- 'Typical ratings' refers to the average OPR;
- 'Initial performance scores' refers to the average starting performance.

- "highest-ranking star in the constellation of performance metrics" metaphorically refers to the MAX(metric_id) from the performance_metrics table;
- "captain of the ship" metaphorically refers to the username of the user who has the report associated with the said metric;
- The chain of command, here, is symbolized by the nested SQL queries, linking the performance metrics to the report, and then to the user.

sql:
SELECT username 
FROM users 
WHERE user_id = (
    SELECT user_id 
    FROM reports 
    WHERE report_id = (
        SELECT MAX(metric_id) 
        FROM performance_metrics
    )
);

SELECT teams.team_name, teams.coach_name, reports.report_data
FROM teams
JOIN reports ON teams.team_id = reports.user_id;

SELECT team_id, team_name
FROM teams
WHERE team_id IN (
    SELECT team_id 
    FROM performance_metrics
    WHERE climbing_avg > (
        SELECT AVG(climbing_avg) FROM performance_metrics
    )
);

